Containers are a form of operating-system-level virtualization. They package an application and its dependencies into a self-contained unit, isolating it from other processes on the same host
. This allows multiple containers to run side-by-side on one OS, making applications portable and resource-efficient.
Docker is a popular container platform. It uses the host’s kernel features (namespaces and cgroups) to isolate containers
. Docker provides a client-server architecture: the Docker Engine (daemon) manages containers and images, and the Docker CLI (client) sends commands to it.
Containers vs. Virtual Machines: Unlike VMs, containers share the host OS kernel rather than running full guest OS instances
. This makes containers more lightweight and faster to start, but they all rely on the same kernel. In contrast, VMs each include their own OS and virtualized hardware. A simple diagram (below) compares these architectures.
Core components: Key Docker concepts include images (read-only templates), containers (running instances of images), Dockerfile (instructions to build images), and registries (repositories like Docker Hub to store images).
Basic Docker commands: Common commands include docker pull (download an image), docker run (create and start a container from an image)
, docker ps (list containers), docker stop/docker rm (stop/remove containers), and docker images (list images). For example, docker run -it ubuntu bash launches an interactive Ubuntu shell. Running docker info shows system summary (number of containers and images)
.
