Section-by-Section Summaries
Containers and Virtualization:

A container packages an application and all its dependencies (libraries, binaries, config) into a single unit
. It runs on top of the host OS but is isolated: it sees its own view of the file system, processes, network, etc. Containers use host kernel features (namespaces for resource/view isolation and cgroups for resource limits) to keep processes separate
.
Think of a container as a “portable cake recipe”: the image (recipe) contains everything needed, and each running container (cake) is created from that image
.
Why use containers? They ensure consistency across environments (dev/test/prod), speed up deployment (no booting a full OS), and improve resource utilization. Containers start quickly because they don’t need a full guest OS, and one host can run many containers with minimal overhead.
Container vs. Virtual Machine:

Key difference: Containers share the host OS kernel, whereas VMs include their own OS kernel on virtualized hardware
.
In a VM setup, each VM has a hypervisor and a guest OS. In a container setup, the host kernel is shared and a container engine (like Docker Engine) manages containers directly.
Because of this, containers are lighter-weight than VMs. For example, multiple Linux containers can run on a Windows host (with a minimal Linux VM under the hood), or on a single Linux server, without needing separate OS instances
.
